  "prompt": "Why is Redis written in C, not C++?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why Redis is written in C rather than C++:\n\n1. Performance\n- C provides lower-level control and minimal runtime overhead\n- C has less abstraction and direct memory management\n- C++ introduces additional runtime complexity with features like virtual methods and RTTI\n\n2. Simplicity\n- C is a simpler language with fewer language features\n- Redis aims for a clean, straightforward implementation\n- C allows more direct and predictable code execution\n\n3. Embedded Systems Compatibility\n- C has broader support across different platforms and architectures\n- C code can be more easily compiled for embedded systems\n- Less dependency on complex runtime environments\n\n4. Antirez's (Original Author) Preference\n- Salvatore Sanfilippo (Antirez) was more comfortable with C\n- Preferred minimal, efficient code without heavy object-oriented abstractions\n\n5. Memory Management\n- Direct memory control in C\n- Easier to implement custom memory allocation strategies\n- Less overhead compared to C++ memory management\n\n6. Historical Context\n- When Redis started, C was more established for system programming\n- Lower-level system libraries and networking code were predominantly in C\n\n7. Community and Ecosystem\n- Extensive C libraries for networking, low-level operations\n- Easier integration with other systems and languages\n\nWhile C++ offers advantages like object-oriented programming, Redis prioritized raw performance and simplicity.",
